<Layout title="How Columbus City Council Works" description="How Columbus's hybrid at-large/district council system works — history, elections, term structure, council powers, and how to participate.">

  <header class="page-header">
    <h1>How Columbus City Council Works</h1>
    <p class="page-intro">Columbus uses a genuinely unusual hybrid council system. This page explains how it works, why it exists, and how residents can participate.</p>
    <nav class="page-toc" aria-label="On this page">
      <ul>
        <li><a href="#history">History</a></li>
        <li><a href="#hybrid-system">How the Hybrid Works</a></li>
        <li><a href="#terms">Term Structure</a></li>
        <li><a href="#powers">Council Powers</a></li>
        <li><a href="#participate">How to Participate</a></li>
      </ul>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <section id="history" class="content-section">
    <h2>History</h2>
    <p>For over a century — from 1914 to 2023 — Columbus City Council operated as a purely at-large body. All council members were elected city-wide, and none were required to live in or represent a specific geographic area.</p>
    <p>In November 2018, Columbus voters approved a charter amendment to create a district-based council system. The measure passed with approximately 75% support. The amendment called for a Districting Commission to draw nine residential districts of roughly equal population.</p>
    <p>The Districting Commission convened in 2021 and developed three proposed maps. City Council selected the final map in December 2021, creating nine districts each containing approximately 100,000 residents.</p>
    <p>The first district elections were held in November 2023. All nine seats were filled simultaneously, marking the end of the at-large era and the beginning of geographic representation in Columbus.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="hybrid-system" class="content-section">
    <h2>How the Hybrid Works</h2>
    <p>Columbus does not use a traditional ward system. It uses a hybrid at-large/district model that works differently from most American cities:</p>
    <p><strong>Residency requirement:</strong> Each council member must live within their assigned district. Christopher Wyche must reside in District 1, Nancy Day-Achauer in District 2, and so on.</p>
    <p><strong>City-wide elections:</strong> All Columbus voters vote in all nine district races — not just the race for their own district. Every registered voter sees all nine council races on their ballot.</p>
    <p><strong>Why this matters:</strong> Because every council member is elected by the entire city, they are accountable to all Columbus residents, not just the constituents in their home district. A resident of District 4 can vote against a District 9 incumbent they disagree with, and vice versa. This hybrid structure is designed to combine the geographic representation benefits of districts with the city-wide accountability of at-large elections.</p>
    <p>This is the most counterintuitive aspect of the Columbus system, and research from the 2023 election cycle showed that most voters did not fully understand it. If you take one thing from this page: <strong>you vote in all nine races, not just your district's race.</strong></p>
  </section>

  <section id="terms" class="content-section">
    <h2>Term Structure</h2>
    <p>In the November 2023 election, all nine council seats were filled simultaneously for the first time under the new district system.</p>
    <p>To establish staggered terms going forward, a lot drawing was held in January 2024. Four members drew two-year initial terms, and five drew four-year initial terms:</p>
    <p><strong>Two-year terms (up for re-election in 2025):</strong> Districts 1, 3, 4, and 7. These four seats were on the ballot in November 2025.</p>
    <p><strong>Four-year terms (up for re-election in 2027):</strong> Districts 2, 5, 6, 8, and 9. These five seats will be on the ballot in November 2027.</p>
    <p>After the 2025 election, all future council terms are four years on a staggered cycle. Districts 1, 3, 4, and 7 will next be up in 2029. Districts 2, 5, 6, 8, and 9 will next be up in 2027.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="powers" class="content-section">
    <h2>Council Powers</h2>
    <p>Columbus City Council is the primary legislative body of the City of Columbus. Its core responsibilities include:</p>
    <p><strong>Budget authority:</strong> Council adopts the city's annual operating and capital budgets, controlling how Columbus allocates its resources across departments, services, and infrastructure.</p>
    <p><strong>Legislation:</strong> Council enacts and amends the Columbus City Code, the body of local law governing everything from zoning and building permits to public safety regulations and business licensing.</p>
    <p><strong>Contract approval:</strong> Major city contracts — for construction, services, and procurement — require council approval before they can take effect.</p>
    <p><strong>Council President:</strong> The council elects a president from among its members. The Council President presides over meetings, sets agendas, and assigns committee chairs. Shannon G. Hardin currently serves as Council President. Rob Dorans serves as President Pro Tem.</p>
    <p>Council business is conducted through standing committees, each chaired by a council member. Committees review proposed legislation, hear testimony, and vote before items advance to the full council. See each <a href="/districts/district-one/">district page</a> for the committee assignments of individual council members.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="participate" class="content-section">
    <h2>How to Participate</h2>
    <p>Columbus offers several direct pathways for civic participation:</p>
    <p><strong>Attend City Council meetings.</strong> Council meets regularly at Columbus City Hall. Meetings are open to the public. The <a href="https://www.columbus.gov/Government/City-Council/Meeting-Schedules-Agendas" target="_blank" rel="noopener">meeting schedule and agendas</a> are published online.</p>
    <p><strong>Submit written public comment.</strong> Residents can submit written comments on items before council. Check the agenda and meeting schedule for deadlines and procedures.</p>
    <p><strong>Contact your council member directly.</strong> Every council member has a publicly listed office phone and email. Visit the <a href="https://www.columbus.gov/Government/City-Council/Directory" target="_blank" rel="noopener">council directory</a> or any district page on this site for contact information.</p>
    <p><strong>Engage your area commission.</strong> Columbus's area commissions are the most local level of civic input below council. They review zoning cases, hear neighborhood concerns, and advise council. Find your area commission through the district pages on this site, or visit <a href="https://cbusareacommissions.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">cbusareacommissions.org</a>.</p>
    <p><strong>Register to vote and confirm your district.</strong> You can register to vote or check your registration at <a href="https://www.ohiosos.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ohiosos.gov</a>. To confirm which council district you live in, use the <a href="https://columbus.maps.arcgis.com/apps/webappviewer/index.html?id=7db35f3529294a6d8eaff9dac0958189" target="_blank" rel="noopener">city's ArcGIS district finder</a>.</p>
  </section>

